        <div class="project">
            <img alt="A couple of deer in an urban environment." class="parallax projectBackground"
                src="images/Home/Projects/WildlifeCoexistence/WildlifeCoexistence_background1.jpg" width="4032"
                height="3024">
            <div class="projectInfo minimized right" id="wildlife_coexistence">
                <div class="expand" onclick="toggleProjectInfo('wildlife_coexistence')">
                    <div>&#10094;</div>
                </div>
                <div class="inner intro title" style="grid-column: span 6;">
                    <h1>
                        Wildlife Coexistence
                    </h1>
                    <p class="name"><a href="/about#Joshua_Hill">Joshua Hill</a></p>
                </div>
                <div class="inner intro hidden" style="grid-column: span 4;">
                    <p>
                        Ritchie and Roser (2018) project that by 2050 the world population will rise to 9.8
                        billion with 3.1
                        billion in rural areas and 6.7 billion living in cities; that is a majority of the human
                        population
                        living in urban areas by the middle of the century. Looking at Canada specifically, 81%
                        (30,997,852) of
                        Canadians already live, as of 2021, in “urban” areas which are defined by the nation as
                        having a
                        population greater than 1000 (“Canada Urban Population 1960-2021”, 2021). With the
                        majority of the
                        population dominating urban areas, the ecosystems have been altered to fit the needs of
                        humans and
                        largely altering the biodiversity that once resided there (Gunnarsson et al., 2016).
                        Where have all of
                        the wild things gone? Do people continue to see the nature as being something that
                        exists outside of the
                        city, or themselves? Are there spaces and species of nature that are permitted to exist
                        in the urban
                        jungle and others that are not?
                    </p>
                    <p>In an effort to elucidate the attitudes and behaviors of the residents in urban centers I
                        created a
                        measurement tool (survey) that asks of questions to address issues of tolerance and
                        conflict as well as
                        preference and behavior towards urban wildlife. </p>
                </div>
                <div class="inner hidden"
                    style=" grid-column: 5 / span 2; grid-row: 2 / span 4; background-image: url('images/Home/Projects/WildlifeCoexistence/WildlifeCoexistence_related1.jpg')">
                    <img alt="A tent for completing surveys."
                        src="images/Home/Projects/WildlifeCoexistence/WildlifeCoexistence_related1.jpg" width="3120"
                        height="4160">
                </div>
                <div class="inner hidden" style="grid-column: 1 / span 4;">
                    <p>The School of Environmental Sciences (SES) at the Lethbridge College found that wildlife
                        movement
                        through the city of Lethbridge is among the top three cities in Canada. Movement of
                        wildlife is defined
                        as the locations and habitats that wildlife move within and through. These locations
                        have been measured
                        by sightings of animals in the areas and reported by citizens as well as researchers.
                        SES is
                        investigating wildlife habitat connectivity via corridors in the city and hopes to
                        better inform
                        policies pertaining to habitat connectivity. Corridors include, purposed greenspaces,
                        public parks,
                        habitat islands, boulevards, and open lawns. I am, therefore, working with SES and the
                        City of
                        Lethbridge to improve infrastructure and ecosystem management in the city. Our research
                        is important
                        because city living provides many opportunities for human-wildlife interaction, and
                        negative human
                        attitudes towards wildlife can often lead to the destruction of the natural environment
                        (Larson, et al.,
                        2016; Rupprecht, 2017). </p>
                    <p>In an effort to balance the needs of the people with the needs of the wildlife, I used
                        the UWCAS as a
                        tool to study human perceptions and help sustain and perhaps improve biodiversity. I aim
                        to disseminate
                        this data to the city council with the hope that they will be more informed on where to
                        provide
                        human-wildlife spaces that facilitate positive interactions for all participants. </p>
                    <p>I completed my research in three phases. The first phase focused on developing a valid
                        scale for
                        measuring attitudes towards wildlife in this community. I compared the validity and
                        strength of using
                        frequentist anchors and agreement anchors. I then took the more psychometrically-sound
                        instrument and
                        applied its use to our research populations. The second phase took the survey to the
                        residents of the
                        city of Lethbridge and the third phase did a multicity comparison by taking the survey
                        to the cities of
                        Calgary and Red Deer</p>
                </div>
                <div class="buttonOuter learnMore">
                    <button aria-label="Learn More" onclick="toggleProjectInfo('wildlife_coexistence')"
                        class="inner"></button>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="project">
            <img alt="A children's playground." class="parallax projectBackground"
                src="images/Home/Projects/PhysicalandSocialContextsAffectingPreschoolagedChildren/background.jpeg">
            <div class="projectInfo minimized right"
                id="Physical_and_Social_Contexts_Affecting_Preschool-aged_Childrens_Motor_Variability_on_Playgrounds">
                <div class="expand"
                    onclick="toggleProjectInfo('Physical_and_Social_Contexts_Affecting_Preschool-aged_Childrens_Motor_Variability_on_Playgrounds')">
                    <div>&#10094;</div>
                </div>
                <div class="inner intro title" style="grid-column: span 6;">
                    <h1>
                        Physical and Social Contexts Affecting Preschool-aged Children's Motor Variability on
                        Playgrounds
                    </h1>
                    <p class="name"><a href="/about#Anne_Jones">Anne Jones</a></p>
                </div>
                <div class="inner intro hidden" style="grid-column: 4 / span 3; max-height: max-content;">
                    <p>
                        Our playground project aims to better understand how preschool-aged children behave on
                        playgrounds,
                        specifically in terms of their behavioural variability. Previous work has suggested the
                        variable
                        behaviour can help people learn a new skill and that variability continues to be
                        essential as we deal
                        with our complex environments. Therefore, our goal is to identify physical and social
                        contexts that may
                        encourage or constrain children's variable behaviour. Our current project will describe
                        children's
                        everyday playground behaviour (as there is little previous research looking at
                        children's specific
                        actions on playground equipment) and test how different types of playground equipment
                        affect behavioural
                        variability. Additionally, we will investigate how the presence of other children on the
                        playground and
                        the engagement of caregivers (measured by proximity and amount of verbal direction)
                        affects children's
                        willingness to perform a variety of actions. Our follow-up study will directly test the
                        role of
                        variability in skill learning.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="inner hidden"
                    style="grid-column: 1 / span 3; grid-row: 2 / span 2; background-image: url('images/Home/Projects/PhysicalandSocialContextsAffectingPreschoolagedChildren/DataCollectors.jpeg'); ">
                    <img alt="Playground studiers in their natural habitat."
                        src="images/Home/Projects/PhysicalandSocialContextsAffectingPreschoolagedChildren/DataCollectors.jpeg"
                        width="3120" height="4160">
                </div>
                <div class="inner hidden" style="grid-column: 4 / span 3; grid-row: 3">
                    <p>Our playground project considers behavioural variability from a dynamical systems and
                        ecological
                        psychology perspective, in which variability is not viewed as noise to be reduced while
                        developing a
                        skill but as a feature of adaptive functioning. According to this view, skill does not
                        mean perfectly
                        matching actions to situations, but rather, skill is about appropriately adjusting one’s
                        behaviour to
                        situations (which are never identical). The idea that people use motor variability to
                        learn a new skill
                        is supported by current research, but much of this work is conducted in laboratory
                        settings where
                        reduced variability is still viewed as the ultimate goal. When we study children’s
                        variable behaviour on
                        playgrounds, we take the stance that variable environments are the rule and that, not
                        only does variable
                        behaviour help children learn motor skills, but that continued variable behaviour is
                        essential for
                        navigating environments.</p>
                    <p>As most research studying motor behaviour on playgrounds has focused on overall physical
                        activity
                        levels, we created a behavioural inventory of preschool-aged children’s motor behaviour
                        on playgrounds.
                        This inventory describes the variety of behaviours preschool-aged children perform on
                        outdoor playground
                        equipment. More specifically, we recorded behaviour as it pertained to specific pieces
                        of equipment,
                        including both the intended function and unique features of each piece of equipment.
                        From here, we can
                        assess how the type of playground equipment influences behavioural variability. In
                        addition to the
                        physical contexts of behaviour, we recorded the social contexts in which behaviours
                        occurred. By
                        recording the number of other children present and the engagement of caregivers during
                        play (proximity
                        and verbal instructions), we will be able to ask how social contexts affect behavioural
                        variability.</p>
                    <p>In addition to better understanding what children actually do on playgrounds, our study
                        contributes to
                        recent discussions on healthy amounts of risk. Playgrounds have become increasingly
                        regulated and
                        standardized within the last few decades as a result of lawsuits and parental concerns
                        over the safety
                        of playground apparatuses, despite life-threatening injuries on playgrounds being rare.
                        Such
                        over-regulation may have negative consequences for children’s development: children need
                        a healthy
                        amount of risk to learn how to navigate their environment and understand their own
                        limits. Therefore, we
                        will investigate whether caregiver engagement affects children's behavioural variability
                        (i.e., the
                        variety of actions children are willing to attempt while playing) in the first place and
                        test competing
                        hypotheses related to caregiver engagement. Do caregivers direct children's behaviour 1)
                        due to safety
                        concerns? Or do they direct children's behaviour 2) to encourage normative playground
                        behaviour?
                        Overall, our project investigates what conditions constrain or encourage variable
                        behaviour and may lead
                        to a better understand of what could be lost if we over-regulate children’s play.</p>
                    <p>The next phase of this project (in the works) will directly test the impact of
                        variability on motor
                        skill learning and explore whether variability increases the flexible use of skills
                        (i.e., applying a
                        skill to new situations).</p>
                </div>
