                <div class="inner intro title" style="grid-column: span 6;">
                    <h1>
                        Multi Object Non-invasive Kinaesthetic Environment (MONKE) Tracker
                    </h1>
                    <p class="name"><a href="/about#Miranda_Lucas">Miranda Lucas</a>, <a
                            href="/about#Justin_Petluk">Justin Petluk</a></p>
                </div>
                <div class="inner intro hidden" style="grid-column: span 3;">
                    <p>
                        Our lab is highly collaborative, and projects kept popping up that required a
                        computational method for
                        tracking unique individuals in video clips. To address this issue, the MONKE tracker was
                        built as the
                        foundation for other types of tracking and movement analysis research. MONKE tracker is
                        a fully
                        functional, open-source tracking program built by Justin Petluk. It’s basic
                        functionality is to track
                        individuals through space and time, allowing the user to halt and correct the tracker.
                        This is an
                        important change from other trackers that are prone to identity switches that cannot be
                        corrected. The
                        user interface also allows the user to record other information about the individual
                        that might be
                        relevant for the analysis. The more advanced side of the MONKE program has a Residual
                        Convolution Neural
                        Network (RCNN) deep learning integration, and other prediction filters that can be
                        customized based on
                        the user’s needs. We are currently preparing an evaluation for publication to
                        demonstrate MONKE’s
                        flexibility and robustness.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="inner hidden"
                    style=" grid-column: 4 / span 3; grid-row: 2 / span 1; background-image: url('images/Home/Projects/MONKETracker/Tracker1.jpg')">
                    <img alt="A tent for completing surveys." src="images/Home/Projects/MONKETracker/Tracker1.jpg"
                        width="3120" height="4160">
                </div>
                <div class="inner hidden" style="grid-column: 1 / span 3;">
                    <p>MONKE was implemented in Python 3.6[] using OpenCV[] for the implementation of
                        Discriminative
                        Correlation Filter with Channel and Spatial Reliability (DCF-CSR)[], the main tracking
                        and data
                        collection method. Tensorflow[] and Mask-RCNN[] were used to implement deep learning
                        models (using
                        PixelLib’s [] library for implementation) which predict bounding boxes around an object.
                        We use a
                        pre-trained human pose model developed by Chao Li[]. Our statistical predictors used a
                        Kalman Filter[]
                        implemented by FilterPy [], as well as statistical rolling linear regression from
                        Sklearn[] with Scipy[]
                        for Pearson's Coorelation[]. These statistical filters make predictions based on
                        location and
                        acceleration of the DCF-CSR tracker.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="inner hidden"
                    style=" grid-column: 4 / span 3; grid-row: 3 / span 1; background-image: url('images/Home/Projects/MONKETracker/Tracker2.jpg')">
                    <img alt="A tent for completing surveys." src="images/Home/Projects/MONKETracker/Tracker2.jpg"
                        width="3120" height="4160">
                </div>
                <div class="buttonOuter learnMore">
                    <button aria-label="Learn More" onclick="toggleProjectInfo('MONKE_Tracker')" class="inner"></button>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="project">
            <img alt="A taxidermy of a raccoon." class="parallax projectBackground"
                src="images/Home/Projects/RemoteAnimalScan/remoteAnimalScan_background1.jpg" width="4032" height="3024">
            <div class="projectInfo minimized left" id="remote_animal_scan">
                <div class="expand" onclick="toggleProjectInfo('remote_animal_scan')">
                    <div>&#10094;</div>
                </div>
                <div class="inner intro title" style="grid-column: span 6;">
                    <h1>
                        Remote Animal Scan
                    </h1>
                    <p class="name"><a href="about#Justin_Petluk">Justin Petluk</a></p>
                </div>
                <div class="inner intro hidden" style="grid-column: span 4;">
                    <p>
                        Remote Animal Scan focusses on collecting biometric information on animals remotely,
                        with the goal to be
                        used on vervet monkeys. Biometric information can include anything from the length
                        between body parts,
                        weight, and colour patterns. For this project, we use Depth Cameras to take an image of
                        the animal and
                        use Deep Learning, Computer Vision and Statistics to gather valuable information.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="inner hidden" style="grid-column: 1 / span 4;">
                    <p>Remote Animal Scan is a system of software and hardware that work together to collect
                        biometric
                        information about animals. This system is being built to handle the entire process of
                        collecting,
                        cleaning, and extracting important measurements of a given animal. </p>
                </div>
                <div class="inner hidden"
                    style=" grid-column:  5 / span 2; grid-row: 2 / span 3; background-image: url('images/Home/Projects/RemoteAnimalScan/RemoteAnimalScan_Scan.png')">
                    <img alt="A raccoon scan." src="images/Home/Projects/RemoteAnimalScan/RemoteAnimalScan_Scan.png"
                        width="3120" height="4160">
                </div>
                <div class="inner hidden"
                    style=" grid-column: 1 / span 2; background-image: url('images/Home/Projects/RemoteAnimalScan/RemoteAnimalScan_Clustering.png') ">
                    <img alt="Clustering of a raccoon."
                        src="images/Home/Projects/RemoteAnimalScan/RemoteAnimalScan_Clustering.png" width="3120"
                        height="4160">
                </div>
                <div class="inner hidden"
                    style=" grid-column: 3 / span 2; height: 200px; background-image: url('images/Home/Projects/RemoteAnimalScan/RemoteAnimalScan_Pointnet2.png')">
                    <img alt="Raccoon Point net."
                        src="images/Home/Projects/RemoteAnimalScan/RemoteAnimalScan_Pointnet2.png" width="3120"
                        height="4160">
                </div>
                <div class="inner hidden"
                    style="grid-column: span 2; grid-row: span 2; background-image: url('images/Home/Projects/RemoteAnimalScan/Raccoon_Part.PNG')">
                    <img alt="Segmented raccoon part." src="images/Home/Projects/RemoteAnimalScan/Raccoon_Part.PNG"
                        width="3120" height="4160">
                </div>
                <div class="inner hidden" style="grid-column: 3 / span 4;">
                    <p>Depth cameras capture an image of a scene much like a regular camera, except the colour
                        pixels are
                        mapped onto a scene with depth points. These cameras are user friendly, and do not need
                        extensive
                        calibration. With this, we can collect unit measurements of the animals. </p>
                    <p>After this data is collected, we must process it. Since the data is easily recorded, the
                        quantity of
                        data is large. This means without automation; data extraction can be tedious and take a
                        long time. This
                        project aims to speed up this data extraction with automated methods. </p>
                </div>

                <div class="inner hidden" style="grid-column: 3 / span 4">
                    <p>The long-term goal is to develop software easy for a person to start a new project,
                        continue previous
                        projects and provide information about the data along the way, regardless of the animal
                        or the questions
                        they have.</p>
                    <p>This project's goal is also to create a foundation for new methodologies to be used in
                        this field. 3D
                        point data is used frequently in other fields such as architecture and surveying and can
                        be useful in
                        the realm of animals too. With data available to experiment with, we can help further
                        development for
                        anyone who is interested.</p>
                </div>
