                    <button aria-label="Learn More" onclick="toggleProjectInfo('remote_animal_scan')"
                        class="inner"></button>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="project" id="art_gallery_intro">
            <img alt="Several pictured posted on a wall in an art gallery." class="parallax projectBackground"
                src="images\Home\Projects\GalleryAsBehaviourSetting\Miranda_IMG_3064.jpeg" width="4032" height="3024">
            <div class="projectInfo minimized right" id="art_gallery">
                <div class="expand" onclick="toggleProjectInfo('art_gallery')">
                    <div>&#10094;</div>
                </div>
                <div class="inner intro title" style="grid-column: span 4;">
                    <h1>
                        The Gallery as Behavior Setting: Art, Action, Perception
                    </h1>
                    <p class="name"><a href="about#Miranda_Lucas">Miranda Lucas</a></p>
                </div>
                <div class="inner intro hidden" style="grid-column: span 3;">
                    <p>
                        You’re standing in an art gallery, now what? Are you interested in the art around you?
                        Is it intriguing?
                        Maybe you could not care less? Are you standing there alone or surrounded by people
                        elbow to elbow? Does
                        this space make you feel like part of the elite or an outsider? None of these questions
                        are currently
                        captured when the success of art galleries are measured by curators, artists or
                        operational funding
                        agencies. Instead, a successful exhibition is considered one where attendance was high
                        and the average
                        sweep rate was low (equal to square footage of the exhibition / median visit time,
                        Serrell, 1998).
                        Although these metrics are based on behaviour they tell us very little about what people
                        do in the
                        space, what patrons find engaging, relevant and/or boring, which is becoming of
                        increasing interest
                        (i.e., Canada Council for the Arts, 2014a - c). This project will be the first to focus
                        on Canadian and
                        university art galleries, with an emphasis on the behaviour of people in the space. The
                        ultimate goal of
                        this proposed work is to provide Canadian institutions with the feedback and tools to
                        measure the level
                        of real-time engagement that galleries have with their patrons.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="inner hidden" style=" grid-column: 1 / span 3; ">
                    <p>This is a major departure from previous visitor circulation research (based on Robinson,
                        1928; Melton,
                        1935; 1936) that focuses on way-finding or measuring engagement subjectively and
                        categorically as low,
                        medium or high (Yalowitx & Bronnenkant, 2009). I have partnered with four institutions
                        across Canada:
                        the Art Gallery of Alberta (AGA) in Edmonton, Art Gallery of Ontario in Toronto,
                        University of
                        Lethbridge (U of L) in Lethbridge and the McMaster Museum of Art in Hamilton, which vary
                        in size and
                        region. The data generated from these spaces will allow me to build and validate a
                        behavioural toolbox
                        using systematic ethological investigation and experimental paradigms to answer
                        questions on the: 1)
                        behaviour of patrons, with the aim of defining and measuring engagement, 2)
                        understanding the physical
                        affordances that invite entry into galleries and 3) the social affordances that
                        facilitate the viewing
                        of art in public spaces.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="inner hidden"
                    style=" grid-column: 4 / span 3; grid-row: 2 / span 2; background-image: url('images/Home/Projects/GalleryAsBehaviourSetting/Miranda_IMG_3198.jpeg');">
                    <img alt="a tetrohedron sculpture."
                        src="images/Home/Projects/GalleryAsBehaviourSetting/Miranda_IMG_3198.jpeg" width="4032"
                        height="3024">
                </div>
                <div class="inner hidden" style=" grid-column: 3 / span 4; ">
                    <p>To achieve these goals, my research is framed in terms of Behaviour Settings Theory
                        (Barker & Schoggen,
                        1973; Schoggen, 1989), which was developed by Roger Barker as a more satisfying way to
                        explain
                        children’s behaviour than the use of standardized tests. His theoretical innovation
                        enabled the
                        measurement of natural behaviour in relation to the various environmental situations one
                        encounters in
                        everyday life where the environment, both physical and social, relays important
                        information about how to
                        behave. These environments were characterized as 'behaviour settings’, which capture the
                        physical space,
                        time of day, and the standing patterns of behaviour that occur in our everyday
                        environments (e.g., the
                        grocery store or the school playground). Barker’s work revealed that a person’s
                        behaviour within a given
                        behaviour setting was more similar to that of other people than any particular
                        individual’s behaviour
                        measured across different settings, which suggests that in the moment decisions are
                        strongly influenced
                        by the environment and do not solely reflect personal motivations or traits. It is for
                        this reason that
                        my work focuses on the behaviour of individuals, as embodied and embedded in their
                        environments (Clark,
                        1996; Menary, 2010; Barrett, 2011; Noë, 2015).</p>
                    <p>The major departure point for this project is that the gallery is an inherently social
                        space, where the
                        absence of others is as significant as their presence. Here, other people, like visitors
                        and staff, add
                        to the social affordances of the space, meaning that they provide additional
                        possibilities for action
                        (Gibson, 1979). The affordances of a space can be social or physical, where a bench
                        affords the
                        possibility for sitting, an artwork the possibility for contemplation, a person the
                        possibility for
                        conversation. Any affordance has the distinct ability to prime our bodies to ready
                        themselves for
                        action, called body-action readiness (Frijda, 2007; 1986; Rietveld & Kiverstein, 2014),
                        and while some
                        affordances are positive, other elements, of the gallery space in particular, can be
                        negative. For
                        instance, the number of people in the space has the potential ability to either
                        facilitate or impede
                        looking times, where a crowd may force a person to shuffle along without pause.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="inner hidden"
                    style=" grid-column: 1 / span 2; grid-row: 4 / span 1; background-image: url('images/Home/Projects/GalleryAsBehaviourSetting/Miranda_image.png')">
                    <img alt="Tracking people in an art gallery setting."
                        src="images/Home/Projects/GalleryAsBehaviourSetting/Miranda_image.png" width="361" height="305">
                </div>
